"type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Winfield  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Winfield","meanings":["English: habitational name from Wingfield in Derbyshire, Bedfordshire, Suffolk, and Wiltshire. The Derbyshire placename probably derives from Old English <i>winn</i> ‘pasture, meadow’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country’. The Bedfordshire placename may derive from Old English <i>wince</i> ‘nook, corner’ + <i>feld</i>. The Suffolk placename may derive from the Old English personal name <i>Wiga</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i> (genitive <i>-inga-</i>) or Old English <i>wīg</i> ‘idol’ + <i>feld</i>. The Wiltshire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wina</i> + Old English <i>feld</i>."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":17,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":48,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":73,"year":"1315","